Engage Glutes Technology Process
Engage your Glutes (buttocks muscles) to come into full Bridge: Squeeze your glutes (crack the walnut) to lift your pelvis completely off the ground as you begin to “bridge” up. Do not arch your lower back.
Your abdominals and glutes are now working together as a force couple to lift your pubic bone to the sky.
Even though your glutes are now involved, maintain your abdominal engagement throughout

Feel Back Anchor Technology Process
Feel the areas of your trunk that are most connected with the ground (major support zones). They are likely your upper back and pelvis. This is important to feel because we’re going to shift your connection away from these 2
areas and into your Back Anchor Zone, which is identified as the bottom of your rib cage in the back. You will connect this area by pushing into the ground with it.

Listen to Your Body Technology Process
Breathe. Hold this position at the top, or do repetitions. The goal is to feel your glutes and abdominals tightening and working together to open and stretch the front of your hips.
Come up as high as you feel comfortable. Breathe. You may feel a stretch in the front of your hips. This is good. Come back down and perform repetitions, holding at the top until you can feel that you've fatigued your glutes. Breathe.
I do not assign numbers for sets and reps because I don't know your baseline level (everybody is different). You want to stress the tissues so that your body will respond by making changes to them.

Pelvis Application Component
Play Tug-of-War Technology Process
You want to bridge up until you feel the resistance of your hip flexors. If you feel yourself losing the neutral/posterior pelvic tilt position, do not go further.
You can hold at the top and feel your hip flexors stretching and glutes working. Imagine the front of your hips opening up. Breathe into them

Position Yourself on Back Technology Process
Knees bent and feet planted. Your heels should be as close to your body as you can comfortably get them.
Feet and knees should both be hip width apart.
Optimally you will not use a pillow for your head. Firm surfaces are preferable

Relax and Breathe Into Back Technology Process
Relax and breathe deep into your abdomen and lower back. Feel your breath. Make sure to continue breathing throughout this entire exercise.

Trunk Application Component
Unweight Pelvis Technology Process
Continue to press your ribcage into the ground and pull your pelvis/pubic bone up with your abdominals until you feel your pelvis is no longer a major support zone with the ground.
Your Back Anchor Zone is now pushing into the ground and is your major support zone. Your Back Anchor Zone (the bottom of your rib cage in the back) is acting like a fulcrum to unweight your pelvis.
